The representations of Siso of earth and water in a new exhibition
"People Swimming in the Swimming Pool" from 2022 is a work of art by Vicente Siso, which will be exhibited from January 13 in the "Tierra del Sol" gallery (photo provided by Vicente Siso)
"Vicente Siso: Memories of the Land and Water" - this is the title of the exhibition at the new location of the "Tierra del Sol" gallery in West Hollywood. Siso has been involved as an artist in the Studio Arts Program since 2012 and is now showing his first solo exhibition. Siso was born in Madrid in 1962 and grew up in Venezuela, Trinidad, and Miami. In his early twenties, he moved with his family to Southern California.
Siso demonstrates his masterful skill in numerous series of landscapes, portraits, still lifes in acrylic, pastel, charcoal or watercolor. Inspired by family portraits, his own reference photographs and memories, his colorful compositions demonstrate the full dimension of his interest and his ability in different media. His tropical landscapes and seascapes show in detailed patterns the places of his past. People are also integrated to create important connections between culture, memory and nature. Siso titles his artworks with a mixture of Spanish and English – a sign of the celebrated and so important complexities of his life in Los Angeles County. "Vicente Siso: Memories of the Land and Water" opens on Saturday, January 13 with a reception from 6 to 8 p.m. The exhibition will be on display until Sunday, March 3.
Gallery "Tierra del Sol", 7414 Santa Monica Blvd. Further information can be found at tierradelsolgallery.org.
Adapt the old, integrate the new and thus solve problems
At the district level, we only need to look at Sydney's Central Business District: an originally unurbanized landscape was first transformed into a settlement with two-story buildings with a maximum height of 46 meters, and then into a city with today's towering skyscrapers. To a much smaller extent, this can happen in Sydney's (city) centers around the transport hubs. Even intra-urban districts must continue to develop with a trend towards affordable living space with buildings that, in crucial areas, will continue to be dominated by plants. Naturally, this new living space that is being created must be convincing in terms of design. Plants, landscape design, and parks must be integrated into the existing essential infrastructure.
Our planning system must also adapt, so that those responsible in the inner-city district councils, who are rather critical of changes, do not solely determine the future design of their neighborhoods. One possibility could be the installation of an independent decision-making body that is committed to high-quality concepts that remain below the height of the eaves and that provide space for families, large balconies, and community gardens – and visually, the whole thing must also be convincing. This could be a task for the current government architect of NSW, where a carefully elaborated regulation must be observed.
In the last 10 years, our lives have changed due to technology. Many work from home and Sydney has gained an impressive network of metros and trams. Online shopping has changed our way of buying and thanks to smartphones, friends and family can keep in touch more easily. Exactly such adaptations from one system to another are also possible in our architectural landscape. In this context, the planning emphasis should also be on adaptive reuse and not on the preservation of the old.
Chris Johnson was the NSW Government Architect from 1995 to 2005 and the principal director of the NSW planning division from 2005 to 2009. From 2011 to 2019, he was CEO of Urban Taskforce Australia.
A final proposal for women's equality
Last year, the World Economic Forum predicted that it would take five generations to achieve gender equality in every country. Now the World Bank wants to significantly shorten this timeframe.
The International Finance Institute plans to introduce a strategy to significantly promote the economic rights and opportunities for girls and women by 2030. The plan focuses on optimizing inclusion and resilience through access to finance, technical innovations, and changes in public policies and laws.
"The latest research has shown that both social norms and ways of thinking can change, and that, for example, the integration of men and young people can help support gender equality," it says in a draft consultation of the plan. "Positive results regarding equality can be accelerated and scaled up if it is better understood... how social norms and mentalities influence expectations, priorities, and daily practices."
Changes in thinking are - in comparison with bank loans for women in the countryside or school registrations for girls - more difficult to estimate. Nevertheless, numerous indications show that the integration of women can move mountains. In Iran, for example, women have become the greatest threat to the Islamic government in 40 years: They have refused to abide by laws that force them to cover their hair. In some of the 130 countries with minimum quotas for female representation in government, for example in India, male resistance against women's right to vote and political activity has diminished.
In some rural communities in Africa, civil society organizations are replacing an extremely harmful initiation rite with health education. One of these programs helped Kamanda Timayio, traditional chief of the Maasai village of Maparasha, Kenya, to change his attitude towards female genital mutilation. He told Le Monde that he had "overcome his ignorance" and that he would stop his practice.
The World Bank cites further examples. From 1970 to 2022, the literacy rate of women in Bangladesh quadrupled and women's labor force participation doubled. The country's gross domestic product more than tripled. The change developed its own dynamic. The employment of women as paid teachers and health workers in communities created trust "and made women's mobility and professional occupation socially more acceptable."
The bank's plan targets norms and institutions where the generational change may not yet have occurred. In Rwanda, it took more than two decades for the country to establish itself as a model for fundamental reforms and to promote economic empowerment of women. "It serves no one if women are kept small," said Paul Kagame, the president of Rwanda, when he spoke in 2015 for a fundamental reform. "We must change the way of thinking, not just the laws."
The World Bank hopes to be able to disseminate this message.
Germanische Eisenbahner und Lokführer machen deutschen Unternehmern Angst
In Germany, where employees and employers keep many businesses running together, large strikes are unusual. There has practically never been a large wave of strikes. But currently, the "country of co-determination" is facing a week of strikes, where angry farmers not only block roads with their tractors for eight days, but railway employees are also striking for three days. Now a doctors' strike is also expected, and doctors' practices were already closed between Christmas and New Year. This "Mistgabelmob" (pitchfork mob), as some call them, will put the harmonious labor relations in Germany to the test at the beginning of the year.
The protests were apparently triggered by the government's decision to abolish diesel subsidies in agriculture and to reduce tax breaks for agricultural vehicles. These measures exceeded the farmers' understanding. They also mobilized other disgruntled workers who are already suffering from inflation, economic stagnation, and the austerity measures imposed by the government. On January 9, passenger and freight train drivers of the German Railway began a strike to protest against working hours and pay.
To reduce tensions among farmers, the government declared itself ready for a gradual reduction of the diesel subsidy over the next three years. The exemption from vehicle tax will also be maintained. The farmers rejected the concessions as insufficient. On January 4, after returning from his family vacation, Economy Minister Robert Habeck wanted to leave a ferry. However, an angry group of protesters tried to prevent him. If the train drivers also remain unimpressed, this could become expensive for the economy, estimates the IW Cologne economic research institute. The railway strike could cost the economy 100 million euros every day if production has to be interrupted. The automotive, chemical, and steel industries, Germany's largest economic sectors, are particularly dependent on rail freight traffic.
The atmosphere among the workers is becoming increasingly tense. "Phone calls with fantasies of revolution are circulating," Habeck warned. The far-right party Alternative für Deutschland is doing its best to incite the protests. In Dresden, the Freien Sachsen, another far-right party, infiltrated the farmers' protests and called for "extinguishing the torch."
Thomas Puls from IW Cologne fears that the strikes could damage Germany's image as an economic location. Local entrepreneurs already fear a German version of the yellow vest protests in France in 2018, which ended with demonstrators setting cars on fire on the Champs-Élysées and police intervening with tear gas. Jochen Kopelke, director of the police union, warned in an interview with the Tagesspiegel: "The farmers' protests are probably just the beginning of a large wave of protests that will reach us this year." Germany was the only one of the major economic regions to shrink in 2023, and the year ended on a bitter note: a decline in economic confidence in December. This year could become even more difficult.
Winemakers angered by the waiving of regulations to avoid waste for wine producers
In the context of EU debates on waste avoidance regulations, breweries argue that they are disadvantaged by exceptions for winemakers regarding reuse targets and deposit-return systems. However, one of the leaders of the European wine industry association believes that brewers "should mind their own business."
European breweries warn that it is unfair and possibly illegal to accept exceptions regarding recycling targets as well as deposit return systems for wine, but not for beer. Meanwhile, legislators are in the final round of discussions about a new law that should bring about the change to the mountains of packaging in the EU.
The environment ministers concluded a negotiating mandate of the European Council on the packaging and packaging waste regulation before Christmas and cleared the way for imminent political discussions with the European Parliament, which are already progressing at a professional level.
"Our position is clear," the umbrella federation of European brewers, Brewers of Europe, wrote to the members of the European Parliament and the heads of negotiations of the governments (January 10). "If the goals and regulations of the packaging and packaging waste regulation apply to beer, then there is a legal obligation to apply them to all categories of alcoholic beverages."
At their supreme meeting on December 18, the ministers decided on an exception for winegrowers from the obligation to offer 10% of products in reusable containers in a reuse or refill system, until the end of the decade. By 2040, this share should increase to 40%. This exception also applies to the demand to exclude wine from deposit refund systems. This demand is also supported by the European Parliament and should be introduced within the framework of the proposal by 2029.
Even if the Czech minister and the Belgian minister immediately expressed their reservations regarding the unequal treatment of brewers at the supreme meeting on December 18, they gave their consent. Belgium, which is now in turn to lead the presidency of the EU Council and should therefore remain neutral in negotiations between governments, hopes that an agreement with parliament will be reached by the beginning of March.
Ignacio Sánchez Recarte, Secretary General of the European wine industry association, the Comité Européen des Entreprises Vin, which represents approx. 7000 winegrowers throughout Europe, does not share the brewers' reservations. He told Euronews that a market dominated by multinational brewing conglomerates cannot be compared to an industry that consists almost entirely of small national producers.
More than 99% of the domestic wine industry consists of very small to medium-sized businesses, said Sánchez Recarte. He also questioned the value of the other legal arguments put forward by the breweries. In his opinion, his organization has focused on presenting "relevant and appropriate" information to decision-makers for its own industry.
"It is not my role to evaluate whether the beer industry should have this or that goal, as that depends on the specific characteristics of their own industry," said Sánchez Recarte. "Therefore, brewers should mind their own business and concentrate on their own obligations."
Brewers of Europe has shared a short legal analysis with Euronews that the association sent to the European Commission last year. In it, it argues that wine and beer are competing products that are "at least partially interchangeable," and that rules favoring one industry over another distort the market.
Simon Spillane, the lobby's chief operating officer, said that brewers were already in "a leading position" regarding sustainable packaging, citing the example of reusable kegs that are used around 165 times before being sorted and recycled after 30 years. They have supported reuse and recycling systems already introduced in various countries.
"That is why we are advocating for an ambitious regulation regarding packaging and packaging waste. But we also need equal conditions for packaging legislation that allows beer and other alcoholic beverages to be treated according to the same rules. Every industry should contribute equally to achieving the goals and supporting the collection systems," said Spillane. "Any other provision would mean a competitive disadvantage for brewers."
The Biden administration is letting economic criminals go.
Tim Whitehouse, the former lawyer for the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) and director of Public Employees for Environmental Responsibility, praised the Biden administration's latest improvements in enforcing environmental law. However, he also conceded that such efforts would face resistance. "It takes years with reliable funding and political support to develop a good implementation program," he told me. "Congressional instability not only demoralizes EPA employees but also undermines its ability to think strategically in the long term."
The problems of the EPA are not identical, but comparable to those of the Ministry of Justice. Its Environment and Natural Resources Division, or ENRD for short, deals with environmental crime. Uhlmann, the Deputy Minister for Law Enforcement, was head of the environmental crime sector from 1990 to 2007 before joining the EPA. The EPA sends its most serious civil and criminal cases to the ENRD, which, as a rather poorly funded authority, often relies on others to decide which battles to fight. In the 2022 fiscal year, the EPA transferred fewer cases (88) to the Ministry of Justice than at any time since 2000 and completed the fewest civil proceedings since that date. As documented in the environmental integrity project, the EPA even under Trump completed an average of 94 civil proceedings and transferred 106 cases per year to the Ministry of Justice.
The general procedure of the Ministry of Justice in connection with criminal cases was examined in detail by the adherents. Observers praised some steps the ministry has taken under Merrick Garland as Minister of Justice – such as the creation of a database for economic crime. However, Biden's Ministry of Justice has also relied heavily on key witness regulations that allow companies to delay or avoid criminal prosecution and encourage them to report individual employees to avoid more comprehensive charges. Kenneth Polite Jr., the former Deputy Attorney General in the criminal division, revised the division's enforcement guidelines for companies to limit criminal prosecutions.
The debate about the shutdown incites the conflict of the Republicans
The conservative opponents of spending in the House of Representatives today opposed the party leaders and caused the failure of a series of votes. They thus protested against Speaker Mike Johnson's latest spending agreement with the Democrats, which in their view does not provide for sufficient budget cuts.
Even now it is possible for the Louisiana Republican to get out of the way of the issue, but the deadline for the deliberation of four of the twelve annual budgets is January 19. Johnson has publicly stated that he will not support a transitional law called "Continuing Resolution" to extend the deadline for those four draft laws to the deadline of the remaining eight budgets, February 2.
In view of the fact that there are only nine days left until this deadline, Mitch McConnell, the leader of the Republican faction in the Senate, announced that Congress must approve a "Continuing Resolution" to keep the government running. This means that the Speaker of the House could soon break a promise with which he primarily wanted to appease the right wing of his party. Such a maneuver could cause a lively ideological debate about the role of Republicans in questions of expenditure reduction. This could lead to a partial government shutdown or Johnson's dismissal from office.
Montana Congressman Matt Rosendale explained to Newsweek: "I have clearly stated that 'Continuing Resolutions' are not the appropriate way to fund our government, as the 1974 budget law provides for the approval of 12 appropriation bills. We have had enough time for this, and if the leaders do not instruct the committees to do their work and let the members of Congress vote, then that is the reason for the failure."
The Speaker of the House of Representatives, Mike Johnson, at the U.S. Capitol on December 12, 2023 in Washington D.C. Johnson faces a rebellious Republican faction that is unable to reach an agreement on the level of budgeted expenditures. Photo: Kevin Dietsch/Getty Images
Rosendale, who is part of the far-right Freedom Caucus group, was one of those who sank Wednesday's vote. According to him, the total sum of Johnson's proposal is too high and insufficient to reduce the state's 34 billion dollar debt.
Rosendale was also one of the 71 Republicans who opposed the Fiscal Responsibility Act: the law on fiscal responsibility, negotiated between the Democrats and former Speaker Kevin McCarthy, which determines the basic conditions for Johnson's most recent negotiations with the Democratic leader in the Senate, Charles Schumer.
While Johnson praised his agreement, which would save an estimated $16 billion, the Freedom Caucus believes he could have achieved more. Moderate Republicans who supported McCarthy's deal consider this stance unrealistic and contrary to the Republicans' goal of forcing Congress to approve the twelve bills individually and not combine them into a single vote using an so-called omnibus procedure, as in recent years.
"A new year, but the same idiotic behavior from some," Republican Representative Mike Lawler of New York explained to Newsweek. "Since there won't be an omnibus procedure, every bill must be debated and dealt with separately. Obviously, it's likely that we will need more time for this. And I don't support any shutdown – so I also have no problem with a short-term 'Continuing Resolution' so that this process can be brought to a good end."
It would be the first time since 1996 that Congress would approve all twelve separate bills. According to Lawler, it is worth approving the four delayed bills to ensure an orderly process. If Congress fails to approve the twelve bills by December, a one percent budget reduction will be applied to defense and non-defense spending under the Fiscal Responsibility Act.
The congressman Thomas Massie from Kentucky – probably one of the most fervent opponents of spending in the Republican party – was not among those who protested against the vote on Wednesday. However, he declared that a one-year "Continuing Resolution", with the consequence of a one percent reduction in spending, would be the most practical way to guarantee the functioning of the government and at the same time stop the constant flirting with risk.
The most responsible way to achieve spending cuts, according to Massie, is to approve all twelve draft laws. Many Republicans, however, do not necessarily want to risk a shutdown and thus a one percent reduction in defense spending. The urgency with which the draft laws must be approved could cause a sufficient number of Republicans to ally with the Democrats to extend the deadline for the first four draft laws and to reach an agreement on funding government work, even if that would mean Johnson could have problems with some right-wing hardliners.
"It [the one percent reduction] should be the motivation and the means of pressure to approve the twelve draft laws separately," Massie declared to Newsweek. "In my opinion, we could first approve a one-year 'Continuing Resolution', then exchange our arguments, and if we are then confronted with this small obstacle, hopefully everyone will be motivated to act reasonably. That's how I would do it."
The supervisory authority approves new Bitcoin ETFs – a decisive moment for cryptocurrencies
The US stock exchange supervisory authority Securities and Exchange Commission (SEC) gave the green light on Wednesday for exchange-traded bitcoin funds (ETFs). This is a step long awaited by supporters of digital currencies and criticised by financial observers who are sceptical of the crypto industry.
The authority has accepted ten ETFs that invest in Bitcoin, including funds from industry giants like Blackrock and Fidelity, but also from smaller financial companies.
"The fact that we have today accepted the listing on the stock exchange and the trading of certain bitcoin products traded on the stock exchange does not mean that we approve or recommend bitcoins," said SEC chief Gary Gensler in a statement. "Investors should continue to be cautious, given the numerous risks associated with bitcoins and products with a value linked to cryptocurrency."
He added that the authorization of bitcoin funds does not mean that funds or exchange-traded products (ETPs) based on other currencies or asset values will be approved by the SEC.
"Important is the fact that today's approval is limited to ETPs that contain a specific product not tied to securities, namely Bitcoin. With this, we are in no way signaling a readiness to allow approval standards for crypto-assets. The approval also says nothing about the SEC's stance on the status of other crypto-assets under US federal securities laws or about the status of non-compliance with federal securities laws by certain crypto-asset market participants," Gensler said.
For years, applications for similar funds have been rejected by the SEC. Last year, however, the US Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia ruled that the SEC's refusal to accept an application from Grayscale regarding the transformation of a derivative fund was illegal. This is to be converted into a fund that would invest directly in Bitcoin. The court deemed the SEC's stance "unfounded and arbitrary."
Gensler has declared that he is – in view of these circumstances and those that have been presented in more detail in the approval decision – of the opinion that the most practical way forward is to approve the listing and trading of these bitcoin-spot-ETP shares.
The eagerly awaited approval was celebrated as a decisive moment for digital assets. According to proponents, it increases access to bitcoin investments and could lead to wider acceptance of cryptocurrencies as a serious financial investment. The price of bitcoin has exploded in recent months from around 25,000 dollars in September to over 45,000 dollars. This is partly due to the fact that many bitcoin investors believe that ETFs will create greater demand for this asset.
Opponents of the decision strongly criticised the SEC on Wednesday evening.
Dennis M. Kelleher, co-founder, president and CEO of Better Markets, announced that the approval was a "historic mistake. It would not only unleash crypto fraudsters on tens of millions of investors and retirees, but would also likely undermine the stability of financial markets."
Kelleher went on to explain that "the apparently lawless crypto industry has reached its lowest point in view of the mass arrests, convictions, insolvencies, lawsuits, scandals, massive losses and millions of victims among investors and customers. Who would have thought that the SEC would support it by approving a proven and reliable form of investment. In this way, the SEC enables the citizens of America to massively trade a worthless, volatile and fraudulent financial product."
30% more reports in connection with the use of the Russian language in Ukraine – RT Russia and former Soviet Union
To denazify the country, the authorities appeal to the population to report.
The number of reports submitted to the Ukrainian authorities about people speaking Russian increased by 30% last year. The authorities in Kyiv are actively encouraging the population to report such cases, presumably to "protect" the country from Russian influence.
According to indications from the office responsible for the protection of the national language, 3692 violations against the language law were reported in 2023. Kyiv, Kharkiv, and Odesa are "still at the top concerning the number of violations. Therefore, one of the priorities for communal officials this year should be to strictly monitor that the language rights of citizens are respected in all areas of public life," said Taras Kremen, public language ombudsman in Ukraine.
Kremen also confirmed that a taxi driver from Kyiv, who spoke Russian with his clients, had received a fine of 3400 Hryvnia (89 dollars). The public mediator drew the public's attention to the fact that there is a "detailed algorithm of actions in case of violation of the right to share information or services in the state language". He appealed to the population to complain immediately on the ombudsman's website in such cases.
In 2019, Ukraine adopted a law that mandates the use of the Ukrainian language in all sectors of public life, including government, medicine, science, education, and media. In case of violations, monetary penalties are threatened. Since the beginning of the military conflict with Russia in 2022, Ukraine has been conducting a total de-Russification campaign, which, according to parliamentarians, is necessary to protect itself against Russian influence. Local authorities have completely banned artworks, representations, books, films, songs, and instruction in the Russian language in schools and universities, and have recommended that schoolchildren speak Ukrainian together even during breaks.
Last August, a young musician was briefly arrested and forced to exonerate himself via video message after performing songs by Soviet singer Viktor Tsoi on the streets of Lviv. The dismissal of several teachers who spoke Russian with their students also caused a public outcry.
Oleksij Danilow, the secretary of the Security and Defense Council of Ukraine, had previously explained that the Russian language must disappear from Ukrainian territory because it is "an element of hostile propaganda and brainwashing of the population."
According to Moscow's opinion, such laws violate the rights of the Russian population, which makes up about half of Ukraine's inhabitants. The spokeswoman for the Ministry of Foreign Affairs, Maria Zakharova, explained in February that Kyiv's "discriminatory campaign" against the language was becoming increasingly "shameful". In a survey conducted last September by the International Institute of Sociology in Kyiv, 45% of respondents identified linguistic discrimination as the most frequent form of prejudice in Ukraine.
Celeste is my "small, good commercial Freeware game blown up big, with unbelievably detailed graphics" in the corruption arc, because in the original the double dash is an inconsistent power-up in a treasure chest and in the commercial game it makes me cry.
In general, I particularly like the cooperation of the two games. The advantage of short stories is that you can sometimes "skip to the good part". This can be more interesting and more satisfying. With long stories, the advantage is that you can give the action elements a much greater emotional weight. However, nothing happens immediately, but you also get more.
The highlight of Celeste, the commercial game, is actually just the Pico-8 game, and that has been mechanically and narratively inflated by several hours, making it even much harder. Celeste is so proud of its little Parent Game that it constantly installs allusions, such as the monument, the "2000 M... 2500 M..." development, the power-up, the flag at the top. You can play the original game directly on the start monitor!
Celeste is neither "the good version" nor "the final version" of Pico-8. It is just another version of the same main story. For someone who loves both short and long stories, it is really interesting and great to see how the connection was made so apparent.
It would have been possible to develop an additional medium-length version between the two versions, which tells the same extended and effective story, but with a shorter duration and less absurd production values. I believe that would have been my preferred variant, so to speak, as an emotional arc of tension. Instead, the main arc of tension for individual players in the commercial game is only a small part. It primarily wants to be a large playground for the physics of the world's most popular platform, which in my opinion is still fine.
