So far I've only needed general anesthesia for one operation. This was a "small" neurosurgical intervention, where my brain got more space. I was born with a malformation that caused symptoms after I had children (Chiari malformation). The moment I woke up, I never forgot it, and whenever I watch medical shows, it comes back a little, especially if a neurosurgeon appears 😂. I've had the hospital playlist on a piece of paper for a long time and I really like it at the moment. #kdrama
My surgeon really thinks of everything. He called me the day before because it was going to snow. When the treatment team was taking care of me while I was waking up from the anesthesia in the recovery room, my surgeon saw that I had opened my eyes and that the bandage was in front of my eyes. I mean, all that in addition to the operation. But it was still irritating. That was one of the scariest things I had ever done. I slept and it was already over.
I had my period, but I had to take off my clothes. That's why they gave me this net-fabric underwear that you wear after giving birth. But in the operating room, you are completely undressed and covered with a sheet. Sometime before I woke up, a friendly nurse changed my underwear. Apart from the births, during which I was conscious and received help, or as a baby, no one has ever done anything so private for me. This was also the only time I was in the intensive care unit. Due to the type of operation, I had to go to the intensive care unit as a precautionary measure.
I had to rest a lot because of my operation, so I watched seasons 1-3 of Grey's Anatomy. That McDreamy was the neurosurgeon helped me. I observed how the patient was positioned to be able to imagine what would happen to me. Since my operation in 2018, more about neurosurgery has appeared in Hospital Playlist than in any other medical show since I watched Grey's. How nice that there is art and entertainment to give meaning to our lives.
Thanks to Hospital Playlist I could transplant a liver.
Wow!
I reflect a lot about the fact that millennials were the last generation that could develop relationships with artists without being expected to also see them in a critical way.
We grew up in a golden age of media with a collective knowledge of pop culture that no longer exists.
We were able to be fascinated by things without having to consider where they came from, because at that time one could not simply ascertain that anyway.
We didn't have to question the pedestal on which we placed them. These parasocial relationships were so important and influenced our lives.
That's why we have such a strong need for nostalgia.
When "The Office" was still being shown, my friends and I ordered pizza every Thursday and watched the series together.
That was completely different from today with streaming, where 12 episodes appear at the same time. Everyone watches when they want and sees social media posts with "spoiler alerts" or discusses it in closed groups.
Subconsciously we long for this universal community that used to dominate everything.
That's why so many of us still watch serious comedies like "The Office" or movies like "Anchorman," where so many individual lines appeared that would be memes today.
We all made these sprays assuming that most people already understand them.
Today one cannot assume that everyone knows something, even if it spreads massively virally.
There is far too much data and no possibility to systematize it. If we ever find our way out of this saturation again?
We are caught in a vicious circle that forces us again and again to discover new content only to then realize that the artist is mammonistic or a hypocrite.
Therefore, we must maintain our nostalgia and at the same time accept that the people who created the tools we liked can also have big flaws.
We develop parasocial relationships with greater caution.
For us it is clear that it is difficult to become rich and powerful without stepping on someone's toes during this journey.
Because we have lost the collective consciousness regarding media, we have developed a class consciousness that promotes our critical thinking.
Among us there are still those who put someone on a pedestal, only to be shocked later if he falls.
We are in a phase of transformation and I am curious what will come out in the end.
