It's an absolute niche problem, but if you want to build/customize small robot figures, it's really annoying that you HAVE to build something that is made for war and killing.
Like the zero years. Then there were Bionicles. These were essentially adventurers/heroes with elemental powers, with different personalities and hobbies and so on. But before and after there's only stuff like Warhammer, Gundam, Battletech, with the aim of being a weapon that is presented in the accompanying media in an absolutely useless way.
It is clear, these other sources KNOW that "war is bad", but then they still sell killing machines as figures and merchandise. So what should we do?
I think the solution is to separate between their parity and this fictitious use, just as one does in the real world with tanks and jets, but my brain has PROBLEMS with that.
Because the figures look cool and I like how they are built and how their design reflects certain character qualities. But then with every set there's the name: "By the way, this is your laser sword and your (at least one) pistol!"
This is probably largely because toys for young people have almost always had something to do with violence, such as GI Joe and Transformers, but honestly, we are in the present.
@user24 I'm already looking forward to seeing Berry's 3D-printed family of pacifist robots ;)
@user25 oh that's THE idea, in any case, as soon as I have the corresponding skills.
To a confessed anarchist, for whom it is absolutely irrelevant to keep his identity secret, he still gives his DNA to a biotechnology company to get a dubious overview of his "ancestry". What could possibly go wrong?
My wife wanted that as a starting point. Without going into too much detail, but she believes that some of her so-called ancestors are actually not her ancestors. I want to support her and see the effect of genetic drift using a small control sample. We know quite a lot about our family.
Perhaps there is indeed one or the other in my family who was unfaithful, but if one considers my family roots, which are for the most part poor, all affairs probably happened in mostly homogeneous villages, cities, and ethnic ghettos, lol.
My grandmother left her husband for his brother, and I have a great-uncle on the other side of the family who left his wife for his aunt. My family might wander, but they don't get particularly far.
And now my wife is in a bad mood, because my "extraction" was much faster than expected. I'm in pain, maybe her genome shouldn't be so easily supplicated.
The results are here and – drumroll, please – they fully match my family history. 89.9% British and Irish, most of it concentrated in the Scottish Borders, West Ireland, Wales and Cornwall. The Breton part, however, is not large, perhaps because it is so close to Cornwall that there is no difference for me, or that my Breton family part does not originate from there.
Since I'm around 40, I had worried that there might be children I didn't know about. So far, only one of my cousins has abandoned his children (perhaps).
Blow, King Louis XIV, one of your descendants is an anarchist!
Difficult woman: Are you now, with this DNA test, going to refer to the Scottish and Irish parts?
I, with a plaid Johnston kilt, reading "Elders of Ireland": No, that doesn't fit with my life.
