As an academic, one rarely has time for recreation, but during the time one is not sitting at the desk, the best thoughts come. 💭
Striving more to publish more does not always lead to better results. One must not forget to recover if one wants to become a better scientist.
This is how I recharge my batteries again.
Use both halves of the brain. 🧠
As a scientist, we often use the analytical parts of our brain. But if I use the creative part (e.g. by playing guitar, painting, etc.) as well as the analytical part of my brain, it's as if my mental capacities have increased. Thanks to this, I become better in both areas.
Train the muscles, not just the head. 💪
Sport is not just something for future triathletes or people who want to look better. Sport also improves the quality of life. Thoughts, mood, productivity – all of this is connected. Taking a break and stepping away from the desk makes the time at the desk more productive again.
Permission to relax. 📺
To recharge your batteries doesn't necessarily mean you have to acquire new things. A good movie or a good book can have exactly the same effect as creative work and physical activity. It's important to make it clear that it's okay to relax and do nothing. There's no room for feelings of guilt!
With these things, I've noticed that they've helped me recover. But there's still much more. What all does one not do to stay fascinated by science and to avoid getting a burnout? 🤔
#academic #science #promotion #phdlife #typefully
