Okay, today I hung up the new birdhouse. This is how it looks in its new spot in the garden.
But let's go back a bit. No question: "What exactly does that include?"
Sisum is one of the ESP32 camera boards with a camera with a fisheye lens and an IR-LED that I have from a Raspberry Pi camera.
The reason for this curious shape of this plastic box is the swivelling side wall of the nesting box. I bought it like that and couldn't change it, so I had to build around it.
Since there is no electricity in the garden, this whole thing is powered by a solar panel and a 2600 mAh 18650 cell.
I haven't photographed either the cell or the charger, but this is a picture of the panel.
In the grey box, which hangs on the side of the beehive, is the battery.
If it is loaded, I have a duration of about 4 hours.
But that's what I call a feature. That way the birds also get a bit of private space.
At the beginning I was not sure if the internet in our garden would be sufficient for this construction. The old access points, which I replaced last autumn, would not have been enough.
But the new ones cover this sector very well.
This is almost a shame, because I had planned to install a TP cpe210 link on the roof and point it downwards into the garden.
Perhaps I'll do that again if/in case I install further nesting boxes. I'll probably need that especially in areas further away from the house.
Now the camera is offline and I don't know why. It went offline just an hour after sunset.
Perhaps the battery did not continue charging three hours before sunset, as there was not enough light.
What was a little less than half a day was too little to fully charge the battery.
I probably have to wait to see what happens tomorrow.
I don't have any telemetry for the battery. I might have to change that in the future.
