The development of humanity is constantly moving forward. Even in more difficult times, we continue to develop and adapt. In the cities, there is still great prosperity, and technological progress is accelerating. With the recent discovery of Ignniat, humanity has catapulted itself to the highest heights, but the greatest is yet to come. This newly acquired knowledge, which humanity receives here, can only be valued as a divine activity, and the gods will rejoice in our presence in heaven. The company Karascene has had Ignniat intensively examined and assesses the potential of this mineral as very high. And no worries: According to the examinations, no side effects or problems are to be expected with the elimination of Ignniat. This mineral is predestined for something greater.
January 14, 2543, 10:26 PM
By clicking. The same stream was repeated again and again: the day the world was devastated. My father always put it down when he saw that I couldn't turn my eyes away. Because of his depressed face, my stomach clenched. I always feel bad when this stream plays, it brings back so many memories, but none of them are really good. I sigh softly to get other thoughts. I always try to distract him and chase away his bad mood by at least making him a little happy, but today I'm tired.
I slowly approach the door and call out to my father: "I'm going out for a bit, dinner is in the fridge." No answer. What else. Usually he never hears, he'll manage on his own. I slowly close the door and sigh once more, after it has completely clicked into the lock. I almost forgot to put my hand on the cold metal scanner to lock the door. If there was anything that distinguished this apartment, it was its equipment with modern technology, which was however the case for most buildings. For a long time, no other technology had been used.
On this cold and rainy night, I took my long-delayed exploratory walk through Paltricus – a privilege reserved for those who had escaped the mutation by fleeing or by sheer luck. The night was illuminated by shining stars that were already thousands and thousands of years old. It must be lonely in the universe. Paltricus was a beautiful city, but one felt more like in a cage there and not like in a luxurious home. The city was overloaded with apartments, houses and other residential buildings, most of which were several hundred floors high, thanks to Ignniat. This mineral had proven to be a boon for technology and architecture and had extended our living base. However, the public knows very little about this mineral, especially because it is under strict secrecy.
To free myself from my sad thoughts, I set off to drink a coffee in my favourite place. Because it is said that a leper has circulated in the region, most people avoid it. That's what they call those who have been infected with the virus. That has never worried me – I have had so much luck in my life – and the owner is a great guy. Who would give up a free coffee in exchange for a nocturnal conversation?
When I entered, my discomfort was dispelled by a high staircase and the smell of freshly brewed coffee came into my nose. Anton, the owner of the place, stood as always behind the counter. The place was practically empty, except for a few people in the back. After the long walk, I approached the bar tiredly, let myself fall onto one of the stools and sighed. I saw Anton and he brought me the usual. "Hello Lilith, a long night?", ... "More or less", I replied weakly and became more tired with each passing second.
To chase away my tiredness, I dipped my lips into the coffee in front of me a couple of times. "Are things still going badly since the story with the leper...?" I spoke softly, so as not to scare away even the last guests in Anton's place. He nodded, while he cleaned a glass with a cloth. This place is actually a bar, but I've never come here to drink. Behind me, one could hear murmuring, but the conversation between Anton and me was rather short this evening. With a short greeting and a bit more energy than before, I left the place.
It was generally not the best idea to walk through the dark streets late at night. But still better than staying in this stuffy apartment and listening to the neighbors having sex. You heard them more often than your own music. With a short sigh, I again directed my gaze to the road ahead of me. I'll probably go to Al's shop, the pawn shop, to pass the time looking at this interesting trinket. When I heard the footsteps right behind me, I regretted my decision. Maybe I'm worrying too much, but in this area, you're only really there if you intend to get robbed or beaten up. The place was infamous for the mafia and gang crime...
Actually happy. Only half of humanity is left, and yet we don't stop hitting each other over the head. I went faster, the pawn shop was right around the corner, and inside I was safe. When I stood in front of a clearly lit sign with the inscription "Alborn's Pawn Shop," a quick glance over my shoulder confirmed that I was no longer being pursued. With a quieter step, I entered the shop. This place was rather out of the way, as Alborn often took in mutants who were illegally in Paltricus. It was dark in the shop, and AI was curiously not there either. No fugitives. Nothing. Something was curious here.
Carefully, I slipped into the back part of the shop, where one could hear murmuring and low voices behind a metal grate that could be removed with a few hand movements. I crawled into the ventilation shaft – for the moment the simplest and safest method. When I pushed myself forward, I heard conversations between men in strange clothes. Then I saw AI in chains. It was clear that they would eventually come to catch him.
I really liked Alborn, but that was too difficult for me. I really shouldn't stick my nose into other people's business, especially not if they are just looking for a fight with concentrated state power. Still, I couldn't help it. Sighing softly, I twisted the lever under me out of its fixation and let myself down into the quiet room. "Psst. AI. AI!" I whispered, and when he didn't answer, I got louder. "Lilith? What are you doing here? You have to go, otherwise they'll take you."
"Just say...", I whispered to myself. While we were trying to loosen the chains around his arm, voices approached and the low footsteps became louder and louder. "Quick! Get back into the shaft and disappear. Don't come back under any circumstances. If we see each other again, then not in this city." He spoke quickly and the panic in his eyes certainly didn't contribute to my calmness. I followed his advice. I couldn't stay any longer. Damn it. After I left the ventilation shaft, I ran away. It hurt to lose such a loyal friend. Were they taking him to another city? So many thoughts went through my head. I was so angry, but also sad. I had intensively studied external cities and the capital of the infected. It was called Alcatraz, after the prison of the same name. The name fit very well with what I had read. Not to mention that the non-mutants had cut off all land connections to the areas with infected. A tragic story.
A canine quietness surrounded me on the way home. Thoughts swirled in my head and I was almost torn apart because I hadn't been able to help AI. When I finally arrived home after this terrible walk, I was close to tears and the rumbling from the levels above me could have put anyone in fear and terror. My father had already fallen asleep on the sofa. A rerun of a film that was about 10-12 years old was playing. Sighing, I slipped into my room. I lay down on my bed. I could barely keep my eyes open and fell asleep immediately.
EXPLOSION
January 19, 2543, 2:34 PM
Time passed like the wind. A few days ago Alborn had been taken away. I didn't know where. Just that they had taken him somewhere. The men's clothes seemed familiar to me, but I just couldn't remember where from. Sighing, I placed my hands on the system in front of me that glowed red and purple – hacking it would have been easy for me. I doubt they additionally secured that... But I should better leave it be. But of course, I pushed my moral doubts aside. My finger moved tele-guided over the keyboard and called up different monitors. Damn, I'm good. I was well-known on some websites, there they called me "GHOST". A very impressive name. Admittedly, I use SPI3RT on every website, but I like the thought that I got it from others.
I downloaded the surveillance camera footage to my mobile device and watched each one carefully. Nothing. As if they had never been there. That makes no sense. The cameras are well secured, even against external access. How...? DAMN. Annoyed, I got up to chase the thoughts out of my head. I went to the door, pulled on my trousers and took my keys. "I'll be gone for a moment, Dad." Silence. That's normal, he never answered anyway. He was probably busy with something more important than me again.
When I left my apartment, I shivered briefly and a shiver ran down my spine. Disturbing. I ignored the feeling and forced myself to go to the pawn shop and do some research. But my legs carried me to Anton's small bar. It was very quiet there and I really needed someone to talk to. Who would be better suited than a bartender who owes you money?
It was extremely full, full of people I had never seen before. Anton actually always worked alone and he was certainly stressed because of the many guests. "I'd like a coffee." I deliberately spoke in a low voice to annoy him a little. He turned around briefly and I had to laugh quietly when I saw the relief on his face. "Oh, Lilith, don't scare me like that...", he said softly with a tired voice. "It looks like you have a lot to do... Can I help? There's a lot going on here." I certainly didn't feel like serving these strangers, but I felt bad for Anton because he had to manage the crowd all by himself. "Would you do that? You'll get your money later...", he mumbled and looked at me with his puppy dog eyes. Advanced war tactics...
After I had exchanged my clothes for a kind of work uniform, I helped Anton at the bar. Despite the attempts to flirt and attract my attention, which honestly didn't really bother me, the work went smoothly. After the shift, I'll talk to Anton. I have to forget AI, even though I know that I will do further research in his pawn shop after this shift at the bar, but still...
Flames shot from Thassalin's throat as the gigantic Thraki set a certain part of the forest ablaze and circled overhead to identify movements. Curiously, the unsettling scream behind him subsided as he slowed down. Thassalin had forgotten the passengers on his back.
"What are you doing, Tenuk, you have already transformed into a Thracian!"
"If I fly myself, that's completely different than suddenly being pulled up by a gigantic pink dragon!"
"It wasn't that bad, was it, Kayel?"
Kayel obviously didn't have the same opinion as Nyssi. He looked less black than usual and his nails had dug so deep into Thassalin's back that Traki was bleeding. Thassalin apparently didn't mind. Nevertheless, he understood that he had scared his new friends and sat down in a clearing.
"I'm sick, but I've tasted something. That's why I had to deal with it!"
"But did you have to drag us along?", Tenuk grumbled, when he climbed off Thassalin's back and slid onto his tail. "And we left Retvik behind! We left our big and strong fighter alone! How is he supposed to follow us?"
"He'll probably have a good idea...", Nyssi mumbled. "Retvik isn't the fastest, but he's not stupid."
"Yes, but can Retvik manage?"
She nodded and turned to Tenuk. "Of course he can drive."
"Have you ever seen Retvik drive a vehicle? He doesn't have a truck like you, and I haven't even seen him drive a small car like Kayel's. Besides, he only just started taking the car to work because you always drive us. He only has his bike."
Laughter interrupted her. Thassalin suddenly seemed to find something extremely curious, but no one knew why he was laughing. It took a little too long for Thassalin to calm down.
"I'm sick, but I imagined your gigantic friend in armor on such a tiny children's bike from back then. That was hilarious to swallow! I wish I had X a way of telepathy. A wonderful imagination! One that I cannot share!"
Kayel sighed, because he could imagine Thassalin's thoughts. "Yes, that's true. But why did you suddenly fly away?"
Thassalin grunted, stood up and disappeared. When he returned after a short time, he threw something inanimate at their feet. It was an Orothrack, a very rare, white-gold creature. But its head was missing. "ANOTHER DEAD ONE. I HEAR YOUR SCREAMS. I SMELL YOUR BLOOD. SOMETHING DRIVES ME TO PROTECT AND TO HUNT. AS YISINI COMMANDS. THEY ARE VERY DEMANDING."
The gigantic Thraki suddenly became completely quiet. Nysski and Kayel also froze and looked intently towards a clearing in the forest. Something big and black was staring at them and breathing. Whatever it was, it opened its two pairs of wings and threw itself at Thassalin without caring about the three beings between them. Kayel and Tenuk just managed to get to safety, but Nyssi was dragged along and almost catapulted onto Thassalin.
Thassalin reacted to this attack by grabbing Nyssi and throwing her onto her back with her skillful and incredibly long tail, before jumping into the air herself. The black creature with double wings pursued her with great speed.
Kayel swore violently, as he took his rifle from his back and opened a bag containing an ammunition belt. He hung the belt over his chest, but quickly realized that Nyssi, the Thracian, and the monster were out of sight.
"Hey Tenuk, could you transform into something that can fly?", asked Kayel.
"Do you want to pursue them?"
"Yes, naturally!"
"But... One of them is a gigantic monster!"
"Yes, and? I'm standing here with a valuable rifle in my hand and could start shooting immediately. But then, just to say – it would be good to see him, to be able to touch him."
Tenuk growled, then he took a step back to have more space. With a light, painful grunt, Tenuk's body stretched, his fur changed into scales and his arms into wings. He changed into a normal, light blue Thraki, but his eyes remained red.
"Ascend."
Like a usual Thracian, Tenuk now had real scales along his back. And from his back two spines had grown, which was practical, so Kayel could hold onto them. It took a little too long for Tenuk to take off, but once he was in the air, he quickly oriented himself and tried to pursue the others.
Tenuk and Kayel quickly realized that they were not alone. A second dark creature shot up under them into the air and Tenuk was barely able to avoid a collision.
"So this is the other gigantic, terrifying monster Lanex was afraid of?" Kayel furrowed his brow. He tried to shoot at the second beast, but missed and quickly reloaded.
Tenuk did not answer. He was too busy concentrating on the flight after Nyssi and Thassalin, even though the other beast was pursuing them. Kayel awkwardly turned to keep an eye on the monster. The fact that it was pursuing them was an advantage for Kayel, as he could more easily aim and shoot. Two arrows hit the beast's upper wings. It screamed in pain and lowered itself under the trees. Kayel was not sure if it was still pursuing them, but it certainly couldn't keep up with them.
A good distance in front of them, Nyssi held on desperately and with all her might, while Thassalin made gestures and spat flames at the scarred monster. The creature was definitely wounded. It seemed incredibly enraged, but not ready to give up. The fireballs didn't seem to have the desired effect. When Thassalin stretched, Nyssi took the opportunity to pull out her own weapon, a good, old rifle. Even if it wasn't really made for such purposes, could the pellets at least scare the black beast?
No, as it didn't seem. The creature just grinned and tried to fly directly towards Thassalin. Fortunately, Thassalin, despite his size, was agile enough and dodged, but Nyssi let out a scream when she almost lost her balance on Thassalin's too-smooth scales.
"HOW CAN WE KILL HER?", Nyssi screamed.
"TAKE CARE OF YOUR THINGS!"
"THAT'S GOING TO BE DIFFICULT!"
Thassalin snorted and then drew a circle closer to the peak that he called his home. The dark beast followed, but panicked a little when a ray of fire hit it from behind. It hadn't realized that it was no longer alone. It panicked even more when Thassalin slowed down and slammed his tail against its head, pushing it out of the way.
Smiling and bubbling, she flew up and spat into the air. Suddenly everything became dark, as if the monster sucked up the light from the sky, replacing it with a level of perpetual night.
When Thassalin suddenly saw nothing more, he tried to retreat. He felt how he scraped against the crowns of the trees, before he finally fell into a clearing. The beast seemed to know exactly where Thassalin had fallen and threw itself directly at him, dragging the black mist with it.
"Kayel!", Tenuk screamed, as he slipped out of the level and began to circle to observe Nyssi and Thassalin in the darkness below. "What are we going to do now? Kayel...? Kayel, where are you?"
Downstairs, Nyssi had difficulty standing up. She was sure she had broken something, but her curious supernatural healing powers were already beginning to spread their effect. Unfortunately, this was not true for Thassalin. He leaned exhausted against the only tree that had not collapsed under his weight. Nyssi made every effort to approach Thassalin, but she could barely see more than two meters in front of her. Everything was dark and shrouded in unsettling shadows. And in those shadows, something was screaming and yelling.
An awful armoured tail crashed to the ground near Nyssi and made her fall down. However, she felt that the tail was only thrashing wildly in all directions, without trying to touch her. The beast, what little Nyssi saw or heard of it, was growling and hitting the shadows it had created with its claws. Something shot through the darkness, punched the monster and embarrassed it.
Suddenly a rifle shot shattered the silence and the monster became silent, fell to the ground and remained there, motionless. The darkness around them disappeared and they saw what had happened: Kayel was standing on the beast, all out of breath, holding his rifle in his hand.
"That was... the most spectacular shadow jump I've ever made... Thanto kat'olon...", Kayel gasped. His eyes were burning black and a dark energy swirled around his body. But while he was still speaking, the color returned to his armor and his eyes regained their usual yellow color.
It took a moment until Nyssi understood what had happened. They all knew that Kayel possessed those particular shadow powers. He rarely used them, because they disturbed and frightened many. But Nyssi hadn't known that Kayel could use those powers even in any kind of darkness. And by the way Kayel was behaving, he also seemed to be quite surprised.
"Is everything alright with you?", Nyssi asked then.
"Yes, with me it's fine. I killed something, I'll be back in order soon." Kayel contemplated his work, while Tenuk flew down, sat next to him and changed back into his usual Spast form.
Now that the beast was no longer moving, they could see better what it was. Its skin was black as coal and slimy, but the mud clung to its body. It had four wings and four limbs, all ending in long, slender claws, and two straight horns protruded from its skull.
Before Tenuk and Kayel could ask what the devil they had before them, they heard a scream and something jumped out of a nearby bush. However, this creature did not reach them, because a familiar vehicle jumped into it from the side, so that the monster slid along and stopped at Nyssi's feet. Nyssi didn't want to risk anything. She grabbed her rifle, shot without thinking at its skull, and the creature was immediately dead.
"Oops...", Retvik mumbled from the driver's seat, before awkwardly turning off the engine and getting out of the truck. "Um, I didn't actually mean to do that. Is everything okay with you?"
"You missed the whole action," Tenuk cursed. "Where were you?"
"You simply left me halfway. I came as fast as possible...", Retvik sighed. "May I ask what horrible beasts those are?"
Clearly, Thassalin, who had gotten back on his feet, was able to answer Retvik's question. He was covered in cuts and scratches and seemed a bit confused, but not too seriously injured.
"YOU HAVE KILLED THE CORRUPTED! THE INFECTED MONSTERS. CREATURES THAT LEFT HERE WHEN CORRUPTION ATTACKED YOUR GODS."
"You mean the horrible god-creature we... helped kill?" Tenuk stammered.
"YES. EXACTLY THAT. MAYBE THERE ARE MORE. BUT I COULDN'T SHOOT HER IN THE HEAD. I DON'T HAVE A FIREARM. AND TWO AGAINST ONE IS UNFAIR, ISN'T IT?" Thassalin limped towards Kayel and spat on his head. "THANK YOU VERY MUCH, LITTLE ONE. YOU REMIND ME OF MY OLD FRIEND ARKADIN. EXCEPT THAT YOU ARE NOT AS BLOODTHIRSTY AND NOT AS CAPABLE OF KILLING ENTIRE UNIVERSES."
"Um... thanks... I think..." Kayel shrugged. "So, are we done here?"
Nyssi shrugged. She grabbed her camera and took some photos of the beasts, which were now definitely dead. Then she took out her favorite weapon, the dagger adorned with the god of the dead, and began to saw off one of the beast's horns. Afterwards, she went to the second one. Just as Nyssi finished, the beasts suddenly went up in flames and turned into a pile of ashes within seconds. The same happened with the horns that Nyssi had cut off.
"Well, that's practical and impractical at the same time...", Nyssi sighed. "But at least I have the photos, I hope."
